  <!-- EXPECTATIONS DIVIDER -->
  <div class="section-divider" aria-hidden="true">
    <span class="divider-label">what to expect</span>
  </div>

  <!-- EXPECTATIONS SECTION -->
  <section class="expectations-section">
    <header class="section-header">
      <h2>What to Expect</h2>
      <p class="lead">Contributing to Arc^ means working within a set of shared commitments.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="expectations-grid">
      <article class="expectation-card surface-panel">
        <h3>Safety First</h3>
        <p>High-voltage plasma requires proper protocols. Safety concerns are non-negotiable. If you're unsure about a procedure, ask before proceeding.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="expectation-card surface-panel">
        <h3>Open by Default</h3>
        <p>All work is documented and shared openly. Experiments are logged from day one, not just when results are favorable. Data, methods, and designs remain in the commons.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="expectation-card surface-panel">
        <h3>Learn Through Failure</h3>
        <p>Mistakes are expected and documented. Early-stage work is messy ‚Äî that's normal and expected. A single study isn't proof. Replication across contexts is how we build confidence in results.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="expectation-card surface-panel">
        <h3>Credit & Attribution</h3>
        <p>All contributors are named and credited. Your contributions matter and will be acknowledged publicly in outputs and documentation.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="expectation-card surface-panel">
        <h3>Consent-Based</h3>
        <p>Communities are partners, not subjects. All engagement is informed, voluntary, and shaped by local knowledge and priorities.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="expectation-card surface-panel">
        <h3>No Extraction</h3>
        <p>Arc^ refuses extractive models. Knowledge stays open. Commercial use requires benefit-sharing agreements that return value to the commons.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="faq-section surface-panel">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    
    <div class="faq-grid">
      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>Do I need formal credentials or a degree?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>No. Arc^ values curiosity, rigor, and care over credentials. <strong>Some of the best contributors are self-taught.</strong> What matters is your willingness to learn, document thoroughly, and work within safety protocols.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>What if I don't know anything about plasma?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Perfect. Arc^ is designed to be a learning community. Many contributors start by reading existing documentation, asking questions, and tackling small, well-defined tasks. Plasma physics is complex, but the fundamentals can be learned through practice and mentorship.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>How much time do I need to commit?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>There's no minimum commitment. Contribute at your own pace. Some people start with a single replication study; others become long-term collaborators. Both are valuable.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>Can I contribute remotely?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Yes. Many contributions ‚Äî literature reviews, data analysis, documentation, CAD design ‚Äî can be done remotely. Field-based projects require physical presence.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>Can students use this for coursework?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Yes! If you're working on a final year project, honours thesis, or PhD, you can reach out to discuss ideas. You'll need to find supervisors at your own institution who are willing to work within Arc^'s open research framework.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>What if I make a mistake?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Document it. Mistakes are data. Arc^ is built on the premise that early-stage work is messy and uncertain. We learn more from documented failures than from polished success stories. Your honesty makes the research better.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>What if I want to use Arc^ research commercially?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Arc^ operates under open licenses that permit commercial use with conditions. This includes benefit-sharing agreements that ensure value flows back to the commons ‚Äî not just to private profit. <a href={formURL} target="_blank">Contact me</a> to discuss specifics.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>How does Arc^ handle intellectual property?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Knowledge stays in the commons. Documentation is CC BY-NC-SA, hardware is CERN OHL-S, software is AGPL-3.0, and data is ODC-BY or CC BY-SA. <strong>No patents.</strong> Ever.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>Is Arc^ accepting interns or paid positions?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Arc^ is currently a volunteer-led framework. As the community grows, paid roles may emerge. For now, contributions are collaborative and unpaid.</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FINAL CTA -->
  <section class="final-cta surface-panel">
    <h2>Ready to Begin?</h2>
    <p>The best way to start is to reach out. Share what interests you, what skills you bring, and how you'd like to contribute. No formal applications ‚Äî just authentic conversation about what you want to build.</p>
    <a href={formURL} target="_blank" class="button button-large">Contact Ali</a>
  </section>

</main>